AOPet — third-party assets and licenses
========================================

Sprite art
----------

AOPet ships two animal sprite sets, each derived from a different
permissively-licensed upstream source. `scripts/generate_sprites.py`
fetches both at asset-generation time; nothing is bundled at build
time except the resulting PNG frames.

### oneko (cat) — MIT

Frames under `Sources/AOPet/Resources/sprites/oneko/` are cropped
from the canonical Oneko cat sprite atlas distributed by
adryd325/oneko.js.

  Source repo:  https://github.com/adryd325/oneko.js
  Source file:  oneko.gif (256x128 atlas, 8x4 grid of 32x32 frames)
  License:      MIT

Original artwork: Oneko (Naoshi Ikeya, 1989).

### dog — public domain

Frames under `Sources/AOPet/Resources/sprites/dog/` are rendered from
the dog XBM bitmaps shipped by the original `xneko`/`oneko` Unix
program. The program — and its bundled bitmaps — has been distributed
as **public domain** for ~35 years. The provenance is corroborated
explicitly by the Mac OS X port `mdonoughe/neko-mac`, whose README
states:

    "This is based off the public domain Oneko code."

  Source repo:  https://github.com/tie/oneko (Git mirror of the
                upstream xneko/oneko sources)
  Source files: bitmaps/dog/*.xbm (32x32, 1bpp X11 bitmaps)
  Authors:      "xneko" by Masayuki Koba; modified to "oneko" by
                Tatsuya Kato; further modified by John Lerchey,
                Eric Anderson, Toshihiro Kanda, Kiichiroh Mukose.
  License:      Public domain (no explicit copyright header on the
                source files; PD status corroborated by
                mdonoughe/neko-mac, Unlicense).

`generate_sprites.py` parses the XBM byte data, renders each set bit
as an opaque foreground pixel (RGB warm brown so the dog reads as
visually distinct from the white oneko cat), and writes per-mood PNG
frames mapped onto AO's PetMood layout. No transformations beyond the
1bpp → RGBA render are applied.

A previous third "cat" slot was retired because we couldn't find a
permissively-licensed (MIT/CC0/public-domain), frame-compatible third
animal. Per the project's stated fallback, the third slot was dropped
rather than faked with a retint of oneko.

